## 4. Blockchain Integration — Proof of Performance

### 4.1 The Data Authenticity Problem

In traditional scouting, there's a critical trust gap:

```
Athlete submits metrics → Scout reviews → Decision made
         ↑                                        
   No verification that                          
   data hasn't been                              
   tampered with                                  
```

Proplay closes this gap with a **two-layer verification**:

```
Athlete metrics → AI validates & hashes → Hash stored on-chain → Anyone can verify
                       ↓                        ↓
                  Certificate of           Immutable record
                  Authenticity             on Polygon L2
```

### 4.2 Smart Contract — ProofOfPerformance.sol

```solidity
// Deployed on Polygon (EVM-compatible L2)
contract ProofOfPerformance {
    struct PerformanceProof {
        string  profileId;
        bytes32 metricHash;       // SHA-256 of raw metrics JSON
        uint256 compositeScore;   // Scaled by 100 (e.g., 8542 = 85.42)
        string  sport;
        uint256 timestamp;
        bool    exists;
    }

    mapping(string => PerformanceProof[]) private proofs;

    function mintProof(profileId, metricHash, compositeScore, sport) → onlyOwner
    function getLatestProof(profileId) → view
    function getProofCount(profileId) → view
    function getProofByIndex(profileId, index) → view
}
```

### 4.3 Verification Flow

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Client
    participant Gateway as API Gateway
    participant AI as AI Service
    participant Chain as Polygon L2

    Client->>Gateway: POST /profiles/:id/mint-proof
    Gateway->>Gateway: Fetch profile & metrics from Supabase
    Gateway->>AI: POST /calculate-score (latest metrics)
    AI-->>Gateway: { composite_score: 78.5 }
    Gateway->>Gateway: SHA-256 hash(profileId + metrics + sport)
    Gateway->>Chain: mintProof(id, hash, 7850, "cricket")
    Chain-->>Gateway: { txHash: "0xabc..." }
    Gateway-->>Client: { txHash, metricHash, onChain: true }
```

### 4.4 Hash Generation (Deterministic)

```python
# AI Service — /verify-authenticity
payload = json.dumps({
    "profileId": "abc-123",
    "sport": "cricket",
    "metrics": [{"speed": 75, "strength": 82, ...}]
}, sort_keys=True)  # sorted keys = deterministic output

metric_hash = "0x" + hashlib.sha256(payload.encode()).hexdigest()
```

```typescript
// API Gateway — blockchain.service.ts (matching implementation)
const payload = JSON.stringify({ profileId, sport, metrics });
const hash = "0x" + createHash("sha256").update(payload).digest("hex");
```

Both implementations produce identical hashes for identical input — anyone can re-hash the raw data to verify it matches the on-chain record.

### 4.5 Why Polygon L2?

| Factor | Ethereum L1 | Polygon L2 (chosen) |
|---|---|---|
| **Gas cost per mint** | $5–50 | $0.001–0.01 |
| **Transaction speed** | 15–60 seconds | 2–3 seconds |
| **Security** | Full Ethereum security | Checkpointed to Ethereum |
| **EVM compatibility** | ✅ | ✅ (same Solidity contracts) |
| **Scalability** | ~15 TPS | ~7,000 TPS |

