## 10. Model Comparison — MiniGPT vs Alternatives

### 10.1 Why Not Use an Existing Model?

| Model | Parameters | Why Not Used |
|---|---|---|
| **GPT-4 / Claude** | 175B+ | Overkill for structured metric analysis, expensive API costs, data privacy concerns |
| **GPT-2 Fine-tuned** | 124M | 240× larger than needed, requires large training dataset for fine-tuning |
| **BERT** | 110M | Encoder-only — not designed for generative narrative tasks |
| **DistilBERT** | 66M | Still 125× larger, encoder architecture wrong for this use case |
| **MiniGPT (ours)** | **~530K** | Purpose-built, runs on CPU in <50ms, no API dependency |

### 10.2 Architectural Comparisons

| Feature | BERT | GPT-2 | MiniGPT (Proplay) |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Architecture** | Encoder-only | Decoder-only | Decoder-only |
| **Attention** | Bidirectional | Causal (left-to-right) | Causal (left-to-right) |
| **Pre-training** | MLM + NSP | Next-token prediction | N/A (inference-only) |
| **Tokenizer** | WordPiece (30K vocab) | BPE (50K vocab) | Character-level (44 vocab) |
| **Parameters** | 110M | 124M | ~530K |
| **Input** | Natural language | Natural language | Structured metric sequences |
| **Output** | Embeddings | Text generation | Hidden-state features → narrative templates |
| **Inference device** | GPU recommended | GPU required | CPU is sufficient |
| **Latency** | 50-200ms | 500ms-5s | <50ms |

### 10.3 Why Decoder-Only (Not Encoder)?

The transformer processes athlete performance records as a **temporal sequence** — earlier records influence later ones:

```
Record 1 (3 months ago) → Record 2 (2 months ago) → Record 3 (last week)
```

A **causal (left-to-right) mask** ensures:
- Record 3 can attend to Records 1 and 2 (sees history)
- Record 1 cannot attend to Records 2 or 3 (no future leakage)

This temporal ordering matches how scouts think: "Where did the athlete start, and where are they trending?"

An encoder (BERT-style bidirectional attention) would let all records attend to all others, losing this temporal causality.

### 10.4 Alternative Approaches Considered

| Approach | Pros | Cons | Decision |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Rule-based scoring** | Simple, fast, interpretable | No contextual understanding, rigid thresholds | Used for composite score, but enhanced by transformer |
| **Random Forest / XGBoost** | Good for tabular data | No sequence understanding, no narrative generation | Not sufficient for full pipeline |
| **LSTM / GRU** | Good at sequences | Slower training, less parallelizable, harder to extract features | Transformer is superior for fixed-length sequences |
| **Fine-tuned GPT-2** | High quality text | 240× more params, requires GPU, API dependency | Overkill for structured output |
| **MiniGPT (chosen)** | Fast, CPU-friendly, purpose-built, interpretable features | Smaller capacity | Best fit for the domain |

